> On the table in less than 25 minutes, this Midweek Mexican Style Chorizo Pilaf is quick but
> still full of flavour. It combines the Indian technique of pilaf, a sautéed rice dish,
> with Mexican flavours from chipotle and cumin.

  Boil a half-full #kettle{}.

  Pour the boiled water into a large #saucepan{} with @salt{1/4%tsp} on high heat. Add the
  @Basmati Rice{150%grams} and cook for ~{10-12%minutes}.

  Once cooked, drain in a #sieve{}, then pop it on top of the pan and allow to steam until
  ready to use.

  Meanwhile, peel and grate the @Garlic Clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}).

  Halve the @Bell Pepper{1} and discard the core and seeds. Slice into thin strips.

  Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

  Once hot, add the @British Beef Mince{240%grams}, @Diced Chorizo{90%grams} and sliced
  pepper. Fry until browned, ~{5-6%minutes}. Use a #spoon{} to break up the mince as it
  cooks, then drain and discard any excess fat.

  Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

  IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw mince. It's cooked when no
  longer pink in the middle.

  Add the garlic, @Tomato Puree{30%grams} and @Ground Cumin{1%sachet} to the beef. Stir-fry
  for ~{1%minute}.

  Stir in the @Chicken Stock Paste{15%grams}, @Chipotle Paste{20%grams} and
  @Water{100%milliliter}.

  Simmer until thickened, ~{1-2%minutes}.

  Stir the @Honey{1%tbsp} and @Butter{20%grams} into the sauce until combined.

  Add the cooked rice to the pan and stir until well combined.

  Share your beef and chorizo pilaf between your #bowls{}.

  Top with a dollop of @Soured Cream{75%grams} to finish. Enjoy!